Of Sun, or Moon, by the dim Charcoals shade;
Men are apt to revolve in their thoughts the memory of those lost pleasures they have not a fair prospect of suddainly enjoying; nay, to put a greater estimate upon them, than they themselves would do in other circumstances, where they might opportunely be had. Thus we may easily imagine, their Confinement to a dark abode, their conversation with uncouth and sordid Objects, must re-call into their mind those glorious ones, of which heretofore they have had the opportunity of a free view; and why not the Sun or Moon, as well as any other? —by the dim Charcoals shade.
